Another comment that might help understanding this code: The old LmClassLoader used the "delegation model" of class loaders, meaning that it was first calling its parent class loader to load a class. That meant that it would always look at the entire Trafodion CLASSPATH first and that the methods to add or remove the CLASSPATH from its own list did not have any effect. The new LmClassLoader follows the delegation model as well, but it no longer adds the CLASSPATH to its own logic, since this is unnecessary. The new logic validates once, on UDR creation, that the referenced class is actually in the container. However, if the same class also exists in the Trafodion CLASSPATH, we will pick up the class from there when we execute the UDR (as we did with the old code). This should not pose a security risk, as the UDR is trusted and can call anything in the Trafodion CLASSPATH from within the UDR.
